    "media:imagetext": "International Tributes to the History of Flight\nFirst Flight by Man\nInspired by their observation of the lifting force of\nThe full-color cachet portrays the manned \"Mont-\nsmoke, two French brothers, Joseph and Etienne\ngolfière\" as it made its relatively short (25 minutes,\nMontgolfier, built the world's first man-carrying bal-\ncovering 5.3 miles) but truly monumental flight over\nloon. Their achievement launched the age of manned\nlighter-than-air flight and forever changed the world\nParis.\nMint stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued\nof human travel and exploration.\nby France in 1983 to commemorate the 200th anniver-\nOnly animals had been sent aloft prior to the Mont-\nsary of manned flight. It depicts the 70-foot tall, blue\ngolfiers' historic flight of November 21, 1783. On that\nand gold balloon as it was described by the French\nday, a 26-year-old scientist from the Royal Museum,\nhistorian, Faujas de Saint Fond, one of the many\nPilâtre de Rozier, and the Marquis d'Arlandes be-\namazed spectators to witness this event.\ncame the first humans to fly in the paper and linen-\nPostmark: This Cover was postmarked in Paris, France,\ncovered balloon, now known throughout the world\non November 21, 1983, the 200th anniversary of man's\nas the \"Montgolfière.\"\nfirst flight.\n© Postal Commemorative Society\nPrinted in U.S.A.\n2015. 056.001",
